'''Sarpreet Singh''' (born 20 February 1999) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for [[A-League Men]] club [[Wellington Phoenix F.C.|Wellington Phoenix]], on loan from [[Serbian SuperLiga]] club [[FK TSC|TSC]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

Born in New Zealand to Indian parents, Singh played for [[Onehunga Sports]] in his youth before joining the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Academy]] in 2015, then making his competitive senior debut for the [[Wellington Phoenix F.C.|Wellington Phoenix]] in 2015. He spent four seasons with the club, becoming a regular starter and earning his first international call up for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] in 2018 to play at the [[2018 Intercontinental Cup (India)|Intercontinental Cup]], where he scored his first international goal.

After impressive performances with the [[New Zealand national under-20 football team]] at the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], Singh signed a three-year deal with [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. Singh's first appearance for the senior team was in a friendly against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at the [[2019 International Champions Cup]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Born in [[Auckland]], New Zealand, Singh grew up playing for local club [[Onehunga Sports]] under the tutelage of long-term mentor [[Hiroshi Miyazawa (footballer)|Hiroshi Miyazawa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/player/sarpreet-singh|title=Sarpreet Singh|website=Wellington Phoenix|access-date=23 December 2018|archive-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807031748/https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/player/sarpreet-singh|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web |date=3 February 2010 |title=Auckland's little golden boot |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/aucklander/sport/aucklands-little-golden-boot/QPVFI2P6N2UQPV2H7BWEO23BM4/?c_id=1503376&objectid=10991450 |access-date=23 December 2018 |website=NZ Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bayern Munich sign New Zealand youngster Sarpreet Singh |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-sign-new-zealand-s-sarpreet-singh-from-wellington-phoenix-5359 |access-date=16 July 2019 |website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website}}</ref> At the age of ten, Singh represented Auckland at the Australian National Futsal Championships, winning the most valuable player award and attracting interest from [[Premier League]] side [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref name=":0" />

===Wellington Phoenix===
Singh joined the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Academy]] in early 2015 after impressing then-Phoenix coach [[Ernie Merrick]], while playing for the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand under-17]] side at the [[2015 OFC U-17 Championship|OFC U-17 Championship]].<ref name="start">{{cite web |title=Singh follows mentor Reid on the path to success |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/singh-follows-mentor-reid-on-the-path-to-success-2882245 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201105060659/https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/singh-follows-mentor-reid-on-the-path-to-success-2882245 |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 November 2020 |website=[[FIFA]]}}</ref> He was one of two players to receive a footballing scholarship to [[Scots College, Wellington|Scots College]] from [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] international [[Winston Reid]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Forbes |first=Michael |date=26 August 2015 |title=Winston Reid opens his wallet to help the next generation of Kiwi footballers |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/71435479/winston-reid-opens-his-wallet-to-help-the-next-generation-of-kiwi-footballers |access-date=20 February 2017 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref><ref name="start"/>

Singh began his senior footballing career later that year, being placed into Wellington's [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|reserve team]] in the [[New Zealand Football Championship]] at the age of 16. Singh made twelve appearances that season, with his season being marked by a call-up to the senior Wellington Phoenix squad for an [[A-League]] match against [[Perth Glory]] on 7 February 2016, where he remained an unused substitute. A year later, following much individual success for the reserves, Singh made his competitive debut in the A-League as a substitute in a 1–5 loss to [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] on 18 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/brockie-and-boxall-progress-in-cup|title=Brockie and Boxall Progress in Cup|publisher=[[New Zealand Football]]|date=20 February 2017}}</ref> On 1 June 2017, Singh signed his first senior contract, penning a three-year deal with [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/93255796/wellington-phoenix-sign-three-young-prospects-with-new-coachs-blessing|title=Wellington Phoenix sign three young prospects with new coach's blessing|newspaper=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=1 June 2017}}</ref>

Singh gained a consistent role in the Wellington Phoenix first team midway through the [[2017–18 A-League|2017–18 A-League season]], making a series of substitute appearances under [[Darije Kalezić]]. Following a minor injury to [[Goran Paracki]], Singh was named in the starting lineup for the first time on 17 February 2018 against [[Perth Glory]].<ref name="stuff.co.nz">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/101533321/sarpreet-singh-set-for-prolonged-starting-run-after-glittering-debut|title=Sarpreet Singh set for prolonged starting run after glittering debut|website=Stuff|date=17 February 2018 |access-date=23 December 2018}}</ref> He marked his starting debut for the club with a long-range goal within three minutes in a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/101470261/live-wellington-phoenix-v-perth-glory--aleague-round-20|title=Recap: Wellington Phoenix v Perth Glory - A-League round 20|website=Stuff|date=17 February 2018 |access-date=23 December 2018}}</ref> Following this performance, Singh was promised a prolonged run in the starting eleven by Kalezić, and became a regular starter for the club; after two goals on the final matchday against [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]], Singh finished the season as the second-highest goalscorer at the club behind [[Andrija Kaluđerović]], despite only playing eleven games.<ref name="stuff.co.nz"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/103112669/sarpreet-singh-to-the-double-as-wellington-phoenix-end-season-on-winning-note|title=Sarpreet Singh to the double as Wellington Phoenix end season on winning note|website=Stuff|date=14 April 2018 |access-date=23 December 2018}}</ref>

Singh carried his form into the [[2018–19 A-League|2018–19 season]], becoming an undisputed starter under new coach [[Marko Rudan]] playing 26 games, scoring five goals and registering a team-high eight assists.<ref name=":1">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=From Auckland to Bayern Munich: Sarpreet Singh living football dream |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/116625602/from-auckland-to-bayern-munich-sarpreet-singh-living-football-dream |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=19 October 2019}}</ref> Following a breakout performance in a 4–1 win over [[Brisbane Roar]] on 22 December 2018, in which Singh scored from a free kick and assisted a [[David Williams (footballer, born 1988)|David Williams]] goal, he was described by critic [[Mark Bosnich]] as "the best player in the A-League right now at this moment in time".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/mark-bosnich-says-sarpreet-singh-is-the-best-player-in-the-aleague-right-now/news-story/1144539efa705d655641b7749009d29c|title=A-League news: Sarpreet Singh, Wellington Phoenix, Mark Rudan, Mark Bosnich|date=24 December 2018|access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/109566268/a-wellington-phoenix-star-is-born-sapreet-singh-comes-of-age-in-masterful-performance|title=A Wellington Phoenix star is born: Sarpreet Singh comes of age against Brisbane Roar|website=Stuff|date=22 December 2018 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref>

===Bayern Munich===
After impressing Bayern scouts while playing for [[New Zealand national under-20 football team|New Zealand]] at the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]],<ref name=":1" /> it was announced on 1 July 2019 Singh had signed a three-year deal with [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] for an undisclosed fee, believed to be between the figures of NZD $750,000 and $1,000,000.<ref>{{cite web |last=Burgess |first=Michael |date=29 June 2019 |title=Million dollar man: All White's move to Bayern Munich attracts record fee |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/wellington-phoenix/football-the-million-dollar-man-sarpreet-singhs-move-to-bayern-munich-attracts-record-fee-for-wellington-phoenix-player/MBYMSMF4UWQ4WRXEPSJWESAYYI/?c_id=4&objectid=12245108 |access-date=1 July 2019 |website=[[The New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref> He was immediately assigned to their reserve team, [[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]], who play in the [[3. Liga]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |date=1 July 2019 |title=Done deal: Bayern Munich sign promising Kiwi footballer Sarpreet Singh |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/113870194/done-deal-bayern-munich-sign-promising-kiwi-footballer-sarpreet-singh |access-date=1 July 2019 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

Singh made his friendly debut for the reserve side on 6 July 2019, assisting the opening goal as Bayern Munich II overcame [[FC Liefering]] 2–1. Singh made an appearance for the senior team eleven days later, playing the second half in a 2–1 friendly defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[2019 International Champions Cup]], and again in the other two tournament games against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] and [[AC Milan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sarpreet Singh makes Bayern Munich debut in friendly loss to Arsenal |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/114345115/sarpreet-singh-makes-bayern-munich-debut-in-friendly-loss-to-arsenal |access-date=18 July 2019 |date=19 July 2019 |website=[[Stuff (website)|stuff]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Singh in action as Goretzka scores Bayern winner in Giampaolo's Milan bow |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/singh-in-action-as-goretzka-scores-bayern-winner-in-giampaolo-s-milan-bow |access-date=24 July 2019 |website=The World Game}}</ref> Singh started his first game for Bayern Munich on 31 July, playing the full match and scoring in a penalty shoot-out loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[2019 Audi Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |title=Bayern Munich coach Niko Kovac's trust in Sarpreet Singh pays off |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/114664632/sarpreet-singh-shines-as-bayern-munich-lose-audi-cup-final-to-tottenham-hotspur |access-date=2 August 2019 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> Singh's performance in the pre-season impressed Bayern Munich's coach [[Niko Kovač]]; on 3 August, he was called up for a 2–0 loss against [[Borussia Dortmund]] in the [[DFL Supercup]], but was an unused substitute.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |title=Bayern Munich coach Niko Kovac full of praise for Sarpreet Singh |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/114726250/bayern-munich-coach-niko-kovac-full-of-praise-for-sarpreet-singh |access-date=2 August 2019 |newspaper=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=2 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Borussia Dortmund vs. Bayern Munchen 2 – 0 |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/08/03/germany/super-cup/bv-borussia-09-dortmund/fc-bayern-munchen/3024082/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref>

Singh scored his first goal for Bayern Munich II against [[SpVgg Unterhaching|Unterhaching]] in a 1–2 loss.<ref name=":1" />

After impressing in the reserves with five goals and four assists, Singh was promoted to train with the first team until the end of the winter break by interim coach [[Hansi Flick]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Four youngsters train with first team |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2019/11/four-youngsters-train-with-first-team |website=FC Bayern Munich |access-date=22 November 2019 |date=22 November 2019}}</ref> He subsequently made his [[Bundesliga]] debut for the senior team on 14 December 2019, coming on as a substitute for [[Philippe Coutinho]] in a 6–1 win over [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. Singh became the first New Zealander to play in the Bundesliga since Oceania Footballer of the Century [[Wynton Rufer]], who previously played for Werder Bremen.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Sarpreet Singh makes Bundesliga debut for Bayern Munich against Werder Bremen |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/118203643/sarpreet-singh-makes-bundesliga-debut-for-bayern-munich-against-werder-bremen | access-date=15 December 2019 | date=15 December 2019 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] }}</ref>

Singh made his first start for Bayern Munich on 20 June 2020 against [[SC Freiburg]] after the club had secured the [[2019–20 Bundesliga|Bundesliga title]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user= FCBayernEN |number= 1274319076718936065 |date= 20 June 2020 |title= Opportunity knocks }}</ref>

In early June 2022, it was reported that Singh was close to signing a deal with newly promoted Bundesliga side Werder Bremen for a transfer fee of around €400,000.<ref name=":2">{{cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |date=14 May 2022 |title='A long way to go': Sarpreet Singh 'a long shot' for All Whites' World Cup playoff squad |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/128645871/a-long-way-to-go-sarpreet-singh-a-long-shot-for-all-whites-world-cup-playoff-squad |access-date=19 May 2023 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref> However, on 12 June, Werder Bremen opted against completion of this transfer, citing a significant case of [[osteitis pubis]] suffered in March.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Werder entscheidet sich gegen Singh-Verpflichtung |url=https://www.kicker.de/werder-entscheidet-sich-gegen-singh-verpflichtung-905504/artikel |access-date=19 May 2023 |website=kicker |language=de-DE}}</ref>

====1. FC Nürnberg (loan)====
On 7 August 2020, Singh joined [[2. Bundesliga]] side [[1. FC Nürnberg]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |date=7 August 2020 |title=Hecking macht Singh klar |url=https://www.fcn.de/news/artikel/hecking-macht-singh-klar/ |access-date=7 August 2020 |website=fcn.de |publisher=1. FC Nürnberg |language=de}}</ref> Singh had his first start for the club, playing 63 minutes for the team in their 0–3 loss to [[RB Leipzig]] in the [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]].<ref name="starts">{{cite news |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |date=18 September 2020 |title=Sarpreet Singh steps out of Bayern Munich shadow in search of consistent game time |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/122772601/sarpreet-singh-steps-out-of-bayern-munich-shadow-in-search-of-consistent-game-time |access-date=25 September 2020 |work=Stuff |language=en}}</ref> He made his first league start for the club against [[SSV Jahn Regensburg|Jahn Regensburg]] on 19 September 2020.<ref name="starts" /> After playing a dozen games for Nürnberg of which he started six times, Singh cut his loan short and returned to Bayern Munich.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Tom |title=Sarpreet Singh will return to Bayern Munich after loan with FC Nürnberg is terminated |url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2021/1/29/22256204/bayern-munich-fc-nurnberg-sarpreet-signh-loan-spell-terminated-return-douglas-costa-ac-milan |website=Bavarian Football Works |access-date=7 February 2021 |language=en |date=29 January 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sarpreet Singh returns to FC Bayern |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/01/loan-ends-sarpreet-singh-returns |website=FC Bayern Munich |access-date=7 February 2021 |language=de-DE |date=29 January 2021}}</ref>

====Jahn Regensburg (loan)====
On 6 July 2021, Singh joined [[2. Bundesliga]] side [[SSV Jahn Regensburg]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Sarpreet Singh joins Jahn Regensburg on loan from Bayern Munich |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/125673906/sarpreet-singh-joins-jahn-regensburg-on-loan-from-bayern-munich |access-date=6 July 2021 |work=Stuff |date=6 July 2021}}</ref>

After his transfer to Werder Bremen fell through, on 27 July 2022 Singh extended his contract with Bayern for an additional year and joined Regensburg on another season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 July 2022 |title=Sarpreet Singh kehrt zum SSV Jahn zurück |url=https://www.ssv-jahn.de/alle-neuigkeiten/news-im-detail/sarpreet-singh-kehrt-zum-ssv-jahn-zurueck/ |access-date=27 July 2022 |publisher=SSV Jahn Regensburg |language=de |archive-date=16 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816065112/https://www.ssv-jahn.de/alle-neuigkeiten/news-im-detail/sarpreet-singh-kehrt-zum-ssv-jahn-zurueck/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, as the club did not report the transfer to the [[Deutsche Fußball Liga|DFL]] before the transfer window closed, Singh was unable to play for Regensburg until the winter transfer window opened on 1 January 2023.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transferpanne: Bayern-Leihgabe Singh darf nicht für Regensburg spielen |url=https://www.kicker.de/transferpanne-bayern-leihgabe-singh-darf-nicht-fuer-regensburg-spielen-919094/artikel |access-date=19 May 2023 |website=kicker |language=de-DE}}</ref>

===Hansa Rostock===
Singh left Bayern Munich after four years and joined 2. Bundesliga club [[FC Hansa Rostock|Hansa Rostock]] on 5 July 2023, permanently for an undisclosed fee, signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |date=5 July 2023 |title=Vom FC Bayern an die Ostsee: Sarpreet Singh Neuzugang Nummer 8 |url=https://www.fc-hansa.de/news/vom-fc-bayern-an-die-ostsee-sarpreet-singh-neuzugang-nummer-8.html |access-date=6 August 2023 |website=FC Hansa Rostock |language=de}}</ref>

On 6 June 2024, Hansa Rostock confirmed that Singh would be departing the club after his contract was nullified following the club's relegation to the [[3. Liga]].<ref>{{cite web |date=6 June 2024 |title=14 Spieler verlassen den F.C. Hansa |url=https://www.fc-hansa.de/news/14-spieler-verlassen-den-f-c-hansa.html |access-date=21 August 2024 |website=Hansa Rostock |language=de}}</ref>

===União de Leiria===
On 27 August 2024, Singh signed a contract with [[U.D. Leiria|União de Leiria]] in Portugal for one season, with an option for two more.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=União de Leiria|url=https://www.uniaodeleiria.pt/uniao-de-leiria-reforca-plantel-com-sarpreet-singh/|title=União de Leiria reforça plantel com Sarpreet Singh|trans-title=Leiria Union strengthens squad with Sarpreet Singh|date=27 August 2024|access-date=28 August 2024|language=pt}}</ref>

===TSC===
In July 2025, Singh signed for [[Serbian SuperLiga]] side [[FK TSC|TSC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fktsc.com/en/news/2025/07/04/|title=Sarpreet Singh has signed with TSC|publisher=[[FK TSC]]|date=4 July 2025|accessdate=7 July 2025}}</ref>

=== Return to Wellington Phoenix ===
In February 2026, Singh returned to [[Wellington Phoenix F.C.|Wellington Phoenix]] on loan until the end of the [[2025–26 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2025–26 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/welcome-home-sarpreet/ |date=6 February 2026|accessdate=6 February 2026|publisher=[[Wellington Phoenix F.C.]] |title=Welcome home Sarpreet!}}</ref> Singh made his return on 13 February in a 2–2 draw with [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] but was substituted due to injury. It was later confirmed that he had suffered a [[medial collateral ligament]] (MCL) injury, sidelining him for up to eight weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Phoenix |first=Wellington |date=2026-02-19 |title=Injury setbacks for men and women |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/injury-setbacks-for-men-and-women/ |access-date=2026-02-19 |website=Wellington Phoenix |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix's returning star Sarpreet Singh ruled out for eight weeks |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360940623/wellington-phoenixs-returning-star-sarpreet-singh-ruled-out-eight-weeks |access-date=2026-02-19 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref> He made his return from injury on 24 April in the final game of Phoenix’s season, a 4–0 loss to [[Macarthur FC|Macarthur]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=friendsoffootballnz_irqgpj |date=2026-04-22 |title=Squads named for men's A-League match between Phoenix and Macarthur |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2026/04/23/squads-named-for-mens-a-league-match-between-phoenix-and-macarthur-2/ |access-date=2026-04-24 |website=Friends of Football |language=en-NZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix thrashed 4-0 in dismal end to season |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360967708/wellington-phoenix-thrashed-4-0-dismal-end-season |access-date=2026-04-24 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref> During his loan spell he made 2 appearances without registering a goal or assist.

==International career==
Singh's first international appearances for New Zealand came at under-17 level, being named to the 20-man squad for the [[2015 OFC U-17 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voxy.co.nz/sport/football-mens-u-17-squad-named/5/211001|title=Football: Men's U-17 squad named|website=voxy.co.nz|access-date=23 December 2018|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427134409/http://www.voxy.co.nz/sport/football-mens-u-17-squad-named/5/211001|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Singh competed for [[New Zealand national under-20 football team|New Zealand]] at the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], being knocked out by the [[United States under-20 men's national soccer team|United States]] in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starsandstripesfc.com/usmnt-youth/2017/6/1/15723748/usa-vs-new-zealand-u20-world-cup-2017-final-score-result-recap|title=USA U-20s dominate New Zealand to reach WC quarterfinals again|date=June 2017 |access-date=18 May 2018}}</ref> Singh also appeared for New Zealand in the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], being knocked out by [[Colombia U-20|Colombia]] in the round of 16 via penalty shootout following a 1–1 draw after extra time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12236724|title=As it happened: New Zealand v Colombia, FIFA Under 20 World Cup round of 16|date=2 June 2019|access-date=20 June 2019|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>

Singh earned his first senior national team call-up for a friendly match against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] on 24 March 2018 in [[Murcia, Spain|Murcia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/102565936/all-whites-fall-to-canada-as-fritz-schmid-era-begins-on-losing-note|title=All Whites fall to Canada as Fritz Schmid era begins on losing note|website=Stuff|date=24 March 2018 |access-date=18 May 2018}}</ref> He was substituted on in the second half of a 1–0 loss. Sarpreet scored his first goal for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] on 2 June 2018, against Kenya in the [[2018 Intercontinental Cup (India)|2018 Intercontinental Cup]]. In the same tournament, he provided both assists as his team defeated [[India national football team|India]] 2–1

Singh was named in New Zealand's Squad for the 2026 FIFA World Cup, becoming the first player of Indian Punjabi heritage to appear at a FIFA World Cup since [[Vikash Dhorasoo]] represented France in 2006<ref>{{Cite web |title=First Player of Indian Punjabi Heritage |url=https://www.business-standard.com/sports/fifa-world-cup/meet-sarpreet-singh-new-zealand-s-indian-origin-player-at-fifa-wc-2026-126060300533_1.html}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Solely appearing as an [[attacking midfielder]] for the Wellington Phoenix but often deployed as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker (Strolling 10)|deep-lying playmaker]] or [[winger (association football)|winger]] for Bayern Munich II, the left-footed Singh acted as primary [[playmaker]] for the Phoenix under [[Marko Rudan]] during the [[2018–19 A-League|2018–19 A-League season]].

==Personal life==
Singh was born in Auckland and is of [[Indian people|Indian]] descent.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Sandeep |title=Kiwi-Indian Footballer Sarpreet Singh Shines In All Whites India Tour So Far |url=https://www.indianweekender.co.nz/Pages/ArticleDetails/7/9555/New-Zealand/Kiwi-Indian-footballer-Sarpreet-Singh-shines-in-All-Whites-India-tour-so-far |access-date=8 June 2018 |publisher=Indian Weekender |date=8 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230419114700/https://www.indianweekender.co.nz/Pages/ArticleDetails/7/9555/New-Zealand/Kiwi-Indian-footballer-Sarpreet-Singh-shines-in-All-Whites-India-tour-so-far|archive-date=19 April 2023}}</ref> While at Bayern, Singh was taking German lessons twice a week.<ref name=":1" />

